defs.docs:
This is a library for controlling colours and formatting, such as
 red bold text or blue underlined text, on ANSI terminals.

defs.name: Prefix
defs.docs: Like `ANSIString`, but only displays the style prefix.

defs.name: Infix
defs.docs:
Like `ANSIString`, but only displays the difference between two
 styles.

defs.name: Suffix
defs.docs: Like `ANSIString`, but only displays the style suffix.

defs.name: prefix
defs.docs: The prefix for this style.

defs.name: infix
defs.docs: The infix between this style and another.

defs.name: suffix
defs.docs: The suffix for this style.

defs.name: prefix
defs.docs: The prefix for this colour.

defs.name: infix
defs.docs: The infix between this colour and another.

defs.name: suffix
defs.docs: The suffix for this colour.

defs.name: Style
defs.value: Style { foreground, background, is_bold, is_dimmed, is_italic, is_underline, is_blink, is_reverse, is_hidden, is_strikethrough }
defs.docs:
A style is a collection of properties that can format a string
 using ANSI escape codes.

defs.name: foreground
defs.docs: The style's foreground colour, if it has one.

defs.name: background
defs.docs: The style's background colour, if it has one.

defs.name: is_bold
defs.docs: Whether this style is bold.

defs.name: is_dimmed
defs.docs: Whether this style is dimmed.

defs.name: is_italic
defs.docs: Whether this style is italic.

defs.name: is_underline
defs.docs: Whether this style is underlined.

defs.name: is_blink
defs.docs: Whether this style is blinking.

defs.name: is_reverse
defs.docs: Whether this style has reverse colours.

defs.name: is_hidden
defs.docs: Whether this style is hidden.

defs.name: is_strikethrough
defs.docs: Whether this style is struckthrough.

defs.docs:
Return true if this `Style` has no actual styles, and can be written
 without any control characters.

defs.docs: Colour #0 (foreground code `30`, background code `40`).

defs.name: Red
defs.docs: Colour #1 (foreground code `31`, background code `41`).

defs.name: Purple

defs.name: Cyan

defs.name: Fixed
defs.docs:
A colour number from 0 to 255, for use in 256-colour terminal
 environments.

defs.name: RGB
defs.docs: A 24-bit RGB color, as specified by ISO-8613-3.

defs.name: Colour
defs.value: Colour::{Black, Red, Green, Yellow, Blue, Purple, Cyan, White, Fixed, RGB}
defs.docs:
A colour is one specific type of ANSI escape code, and can refer
 to either the foreground or background colour.

defs.name: ANSIGenericString
defs.docs:
An `ANSIGenericString` includes a generic string type and a `Style` to
 display that string.  `ANSIString` and `ANSIByteString` are aliases for
 this type on `str` and `[u8]`, respectively.

defs.name: ANSIString
defs.docs:
An ANSI String is a string coupled with the `Style` to display it
 in a terminal.

defs.name: ANSIByteString
defs.docs:
An `ANSIByteString` represents a formatted series of bytes.  Use
 `ANSIByteString` when styling text with an unknown encoding.

defs.name: ANSIGenericStrings
defs.docs:
A set of `ANSIGenericString`s collected together, in order to be
 written with a minimum of control characters.

defs.name: ANSIStrings
defs.docs:
A set of `ANSIString`s collected together, in order to be written with a
 minimum of control characters.

defs.name: ANSIStrings
defs.docs: A function to construct an `ANSIStrings` instance.

defs.name: ANSIByteStrings
defs.docs:
A set of `ANSIByteString`s collected together, in order to be
 written with a minimum of control characters.

defs.name: ANSIByteStrings
defs.docs: A function to construct an `ANSIByteStrings` instance.

defs.name: paint
defs.value: fn <'a, I, S> (self, input: I) -> ANSIGenericString<'a, S>
defs.docs: Paints the given text with this colour, returning an ANSI string.

defs.name: paint
defs.value: fn <'a, I, S> (self, input: I) -> ANSIGenericString<'a, S>
defs.docs:
Paints the given text with this colour, returning an ANSI string.
 This is a short-cut so you dont have to use `Blue.normal()` just
 to get blue text.

defs.name: write_to
defs.docs:
Write an `ANSIByteString` to an `io::Write`.  This writes the escape
 sequences for the associated `Style` around the bytes.

defs.name: write_to
defs.docs:
Write `ANSIByteStrings` to an `io::Write`.  This writes the minimal
 escape sequences for the associated `Style`s around each set of
 bytes.
